Instead of simulating water flow from every cell (which would be inefficient), we use a smart reverse thinking approach using Depth-First Search (DFS):

# Start from the oceans:
Any cell on the left or top border can directly flow into the Pacific Ocean.
Any cell on the right or bottom border can directly flow into the Atlantic Ocean.

# Mark reachable cells:
We perform DFS from all Pacific border cells and mark every cell that can be reached by water flowing into the Pacific (i.e., cells from which water can flow to the Pacific).
Similarly, we perform DFS from all Atlantic border cells to mark cells reachable from the Atlantic.

# Key Insight:
In the DFS, we move to neighboring cells only if their height is greater than or equal to the current cell's height. This simulates the reverse flow of water (from ocean → land).

# Find intersection:
# A cell can flow to both oceans only if it is marked reachable in both the Pacific and Atlantic visited matrices.


# This approach efficiently solves the problem in O(m × n) time complexity, as each cell is visited at most twice (once for each ocean).

# Why This Works

By reversing the flow direction, we avoid checking every possible path from each cell.
Using two separate visited matrices allows us to cleanly find cells that satisfy both conditions.
DFS is particularly suitable here because the flow can spread naturally across connected cells with non-decreasing heights.


Time Complexity: O(m × n)
Space Complexity: O(m × n)
//--------------------------------------------------------------Code---------------------------------------------------------------------//
class Solution {
    // Directions for moving up, down, left, right
    private final int[][] directions = {{1,0}, {-1,0}, {0,1}, {0,-1}};

    public List<List<Integer>> pacificAtlantic(int[][] heights) {
        List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
        if (heights == null || heights.length == 0 || heights[0].length == 0) {
            return result;
        }
        
        int m = heights.length;
        int n = heights[0].length;
        
        boolean[][] pacificVisited = new boolean[m][n];
        boolean[][] atlanticVisited = new boolean[m][n];
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            dfs(heights, pacificVisited, i, 0, Integer.MIN_VALUE);
            dfs(heights, atlanticVisited, i, n - 1, Integer.MIN_VALUE);
        }
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            dfs(heights, pacificVisited, 0, j, Integer.MIN_VALUE);
            dfs(heights, atlanticVisited, m - 1, j, Integer.MIN_VALUE);
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (pacificVisited[i][j] && atlanticVisited[i][j]) {
                    result.add(Arrays.asList(i, j));
                }
            }
        }
        
        return result;
    }

    private void dfs(int[][] heights, boolean[][] visited, int i, int j, int prevHeight) {
        int m = heights.length;
        int n = heights[0].length;
        if (i < 0 || i >= m || j < 0 || j >= n 
            || visited[i][j] || heights[i][j] < prevHeight) {
            return;
        }    
        visited[i][j] = true;
        for (int[] dir : directions) {
            int ni = i + dir[0];
            int nj = j + dir[1];
            dfs(heights, visited, ni, nj, heights[i][j]);
        }
    }
}
